Introduction¶

In this project, we aim to use data science to predict the presence of chronic kidney disease (CKD) by analyzing risk factors and genes. CKD is a condition where the kidneys are damaged and can not properly filter blood. Because of this, excess fluid and waste remain in the body and can lead to other severe diseases such as heart disease and stroke (CDC). CKD is on the rise, and it is a disease that can not be cured, but can be treated (NHS). We want to explore which risk factors and genes are common in patients with CKD in order to better be able to determine whether or not one is more prone to being diagnosed with CKD. By analyzing both risk factors and genes, the risk for CKD can be detected earlier on and proper action can be taken to prevent one from suffering from severe CKD.

Information from:

[1] https://www.cdc.gov/kidneydisease/basics.html#:~:text=CKD%20is%20a%20condition%20in,as%20heart%20disease%20and%20stroke.

[2] https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/kidney-disease/treatment/#:~:text=There's%20no%20cure%20for%20chronic,stay%20as%20healthy%20as%20possible

Dataset Curation and Preprocessing¶

There are two unique datasets included for chronic kidney disease (CKD)- a gene dataset and a risk factor dataset, both are collected from patients. The gene and risk factor data is not collected from the same group as that data was not avaliable, however overall we are looking at various factors that contribute to CKD. We decided to focus on CKD as we originally had many datasets from many diseases and it was a lot more data so we shifted to CKD.

Gene Data¶

The gene dataset we used is provided by NIH GEO: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE225890

This dataset contains data from patients with and without chronic kidney disease (CKD). It is RNA sequenced data, so it is showing the gene expression of all genes in the patient. The goal is to use this data to find genes that are commonly expressed in CKD patients, compared to control patients. That way, we can look for CKDs associated genes to find any genetic predisposition for it.

Here, we use Pandas to load the datasets and store them in dataframes.

The original dataset did not load into Python as it was so big, but it was organized(sorted) through FDR (adjusted pvalue), so we had to manually delete the remaining genes to load the dataset in Excel. The genes we deleted were looked at closely, and all had a tiny foldchange (below 10) or insignifcant p-value(above 0.05), thus we checked each as we went through to make sure it was not hidden useful data. We stopped deleting at around 1500 genes, as the p-value was becoming significant (although at 1500 it was 0.21 so still not helpful) and the foldchange bigger - and we were actually able to load it in Python! We are only looking at big, significant foldchange, so nothing we would use got deleted in this process.

Risk Factor Data¶

Our risk factor dataset was retrieved from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/colearninglounge/chronic-kidney-disease

This dataset contains patient data on risk factors for chronic kidney disease. The columns in this dataset are:

  • age - age
  • bp - blood pressure
  • sg - specific gravity
  • al - albumin
  • su - sugar
  • rbc - red blood cells
  • pc - pus cell
  • pcc - pus cell clumps
  • ba - bacteria
  • bgr - blood glucose random
  • bu - blood urea
  • sc - serum creatinine
  • sod - sodium
  • pot - potassium
  • hemo - hemoglobin
  • pcv - packed cell volume
  • wc - white blood cell count
  • rc - red blood cell count
  • htn - hypertension
  • dm - diabetes mellitus
  • cad - coronary artery disease
  • appet - appetite
  • pe - pedal edema
  • ane - anemia
  • class - classification (ckd or not ckd)

We can use this along with the genes dataset to predict the likelihood of CKD. We looked at data on clinical risk factors from patients who have and don't have CKD to understand if one can associate given patterns of risk factors with CKD.

Here, we import the dataset and perform some data wrangling. Many of the variables in this dataset are categorical variables that have string values such as "present", "not present", "yes", or "no". To analyze the data more easily, we need to change these string variables to have numerical values. We do this by using 1 to indicate positive values or presence and using 0 for negative values or absence. For example, 'rbc' indicates whether or not the red blood cell count is normal (0) or abnormal (1), and 'htn' indicates whether or not there is hypertension (1) or not (0).

We also had to deal with missing data. To determine the best method to deal with the missing data for each variables, we looked at the amount of data that is missing and the distribution of the variables. For variables with less than 10% of data that is missing, we replaced the missing values with the mean, since the missing data is not much. For variables with larger missing proportions, we plotted the distributions. If the variable's distribution is approximately normally distributed, we replaced the missing values with the average value. If the distribution is skewed, we replaced the missing values with the median value.

Next, to determine which variables to focus on for the rest of the study, we want to identify which factors have the most impact on whether or not CKD is present. To do this, we create a correlation matrix to visualize how each of the variables is correlated to each other. Then, we pick the variables with the highest correlation with the variable that indicates the presence of CKD. Finally, we keep only the highest correlated variables to continue with further analysis.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

rf_df = pd.read_csv("kidney_disease_train.csv")
rf_df
rf_df.columns

# changing categorical variables to have numerical values
rf_df['classification'] = rf_df['classification'].replace({'ckd': 1, 'notckd': 0})
rf_df['rbc'] = rf_df['rbc'].replace({'abnormal': 1, 'normal': 0})
rf_df['pc'] = rf_df['pc'].replace({'abnormal': 1, 'normal': 0})
rf_df['pcc'] = rf_df['pcc'].replace({'present': 1, 'notpresent': 0})
rf_df['ba'] = rf_df['ba'].replace({'present': 1, 'notpresent': 0})
rf_df['htn'] = rf_df['htn'].replace({'yes': 1, 'no': 0})
rf_df['dm'] = rf_df['dm'].replace({'yes': 1, 'no': 0})
rf_df['cad'] = rf_df['cad'].replace({'yes': 1, 'no': 0})
rf_df['appet'] = rf_df['appet'].replace({'poor': 1, 'good': 0})
rf_df['pe'] = rf_df['pe'].replace({'yes': 1, 'no': 0})
rf_df['ane'] = rf_df['ane'].replace({'yes': 1, 'no': 0})

# converting object columns to floats
rf_df.dtypes
rf_df[['wc', 'rc', 'dm', 'cad']] = rf_df[['wc', 'rc', 'dm', 'cad']].applymap(lambda x: pd.to_numeric(x, errors='coerce'))
rf_df['wc'] = rf_df['wc'].astype(float)
rf_df['rc'] = rf_df['rc'].astype(float)
rf_df['dm'] = rf_df['dm'].astype(float)
rf_df['cad'] = rf_df['cad'].astype(float)

# for columns with less than 10% of data missing, replace with mean
rf_df.shape # (280, 26)
for col in rf_df.columns:
  if(sum(rf_df[col].isna()) <= 28):
    avg = rf_df[col].mean()
    rf_df[col].fillna(avg, inplace=True)

# replacing null values with mean if the data is normally distributed, median if skewed
rf_df.boxplot(['sg', 'hemo', 'pcv', 'rc', 'al'])

# 'sg' is normally ditributed, so replace missing values with the mean
rf_df['sg'].fillna(rf_df['sg'].mean(), inplace=True)

# 'hemo', 'pcv', and 'rc' are all negatively skewed and have one outlier. 'al' is heavily positively skewed.
# Replace missing data with median
for col in ['hemo', 'pcv', 'rc', 'al']:
  med = rf_df[col].median()
  rf_df[col] = rf_df[col].apply(lambda x: med if pd.isnull(x) else x)

# To determine which variables are important to analyze, we want to see which variables have the most correlation with the 'classification'.
corr = rf_df.corr()

# getting the top correlated variables with the 'classification' column (ckd or notckd)
corr_with_class = corr['classification'].abs()
corr_with_class = corr_with_class.drop('classification')
corr_with_class = corr_with_class.drop('id')
top_7 = corr_with_class.nlargest(7)
print(top_7)
# The 7 strongest correlated variables are 'sg' (0.7579), 'hemo' (0.7560), 'pcv' (0.7276), 'rc' (0.6833), 'al' (0.6354), 'htn' (0.5879), and 'dm' (0.5878).

# keep only the columns of interest
rf_df = rf_df[['sg', 'hemo', 'pcv', 'rc', 'al', 'htn', 'dm', 'classification']]
# rename columns for clarity
new_cols = ['spec_grav', 'hemoglobin', 'packed_cell_vol', 'red_b_cells', 'albumin', 'hypertension', 'diabetes', 'ckd_class']
rf_df.columns = new_cols
rf_df

Exploratory Data Analysis for Gene Data¶

1. Pearson Correlation

In understanding if a gene is significantly showing regulation, we want to check there is correlation in samples, and they are actually regulated in a direction. Patient data is variable as humans are naturally going to have genetic varaition, but if all samples in a group(C or E) are correlated, then a defined gene can be possibly making the changes genetically regulated.

We want to understand if these samples are correlated to themselves enough to prove its not just random genetic changes

2. Mann-Whitney Test

We want to understand whether the differences in the gene expression in groups are large enough to be understood as really upregulated and if the change in expression is relevant enough to consider disease relation to the disease.

We will peform a Mann-Whitney test, we want to compare the means of genes expressed in control and pkd patient samples. We assume the groups are independent of one another. There is so few samples, there is no way to assume normal distribution with only 3 controls-thus Mann- Whitney is ideal. We can use a significance level of .05 for the test.

The genes will be tested separately, so PTIX2 gets its own test, and ALX1 also does. The point is to look at each gene, to test if there is difference in each expression in patients in each group and determine if it is significant as a candidate gene to have relation to disease.

We will also graph the data to show the differences.

The dataset gave p-values and adjusted pvalue(FDR) itself, but I do not know how they were calculated, thus it is better to do my own analysis.

Null Hypothesis: There is no difference among the sample means of the levels of gene expression, in the genes of interest, within control samples versus CKD patient samples.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a difference among the sample means of the levels of gene expression, in the genes of interest, within control samples versu CKD patient samples.

Exploratory Data Analysis for Risk Factor Data¶

1. Chi-Squared Test

We want to determine if there is a significant association between specific gravity (sg) levels and whether or not the person has chronic kidney disease. To determine this, we conduct a Chi-Squared Test to compare the 'sg' and 'classification' variables. The 'sg' variable is nominal, so the values are one of 5 possible values (1.005,1.010,1.015,1.020,1.025). The 'classification' variable tells whether the entry is a ckd patient (1) or not (0). We will use a signifiance level of 0.01 for this test.

Null Hypothesis: The level of specific gravity does not effect the likelihood of having chronic kidney disease.

Alternative Hypothesis: The level of specific gravity does have an effect on the likelihood of having chronic kidney disease.

In [24]:
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(rf_df['spec_grav'], rf_df['ckd_class'])

The plot above shows the relationship between the sg level and the ckd classification. It shows that the lower sg levels had more cases classified as ckd.

After running the Chi-Squared Test, we get a p-value of 2.507e-37. Based on the obtained p-value, we reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is less than the significance level: 2.507e-37 < 0.01. Therefore, we can conclude that the sg level does indeed have an effect on whether or not someone has chronic kidney disease.

2. ANOVA Test

Now that we know that lower levels of specific gravity (sg) correspond to more cases of chronic kidney disease (ckd), we want to determine if the average number of cases of ckd differ among the different groups of the lower sg levels, namely 1.005, 1.01, 1.015, and 1.017. To determine this, we conduct an ANOVA Test. The 'sg' variable is nominal, so the values are one of 5 possible values (1.005,1.010,1.015,1.020,1.025). The 'classification' variable tells whether the entry is a ckd patient (1) or not (0). We will use a signifiance level of 0.01 for this test.

Null Hypothesis: The mean number of cases of chronic kidney disease are about the same among the different groups of sg levels.

Alternative Hypothesis: The mean number of cases of chronic kidney disease are different among at least 2 different groups of sg levels.

In [25]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# anova test
groups = [rf_df[rf_df['spec_grav'] == sg_level]['ckd_class'] for sg_level in rf_df['spec_grav'].unique()]
f_statistic, p_value = f_oneway(*groups)
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

# plotting proportion of ckd cases within each sg level category
csg = rf_df.groupby('spec_grav')['ckd_class'].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
csg.plot(kind='bar', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Proportion of CKD cases by specfic gravity level')
plt.xlabel('specific gravity level')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of CKD Cases')
plt.show()

P-value: 4.19183799931205e-60

The plot above shows the proportion of ckd cases by sg level. It shows that with low levels of sg (1.005, 1.01, and 1.015), 100% of the patients have ckd.

The p-value produced by the ANOVA test is 4.1918e-60. This is very small and less than the significance level of 0.01. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the mean number of ckd cases based on sg level is indeed different. This implies that lower levels of sg result in ckd.

A Post Hoc Test can be helpful to identify which specific groups are different from each other and how they are different. For example, if people with a sg level of 1.005 are more likely to have ckd compared to people with a sg level of 1.01 and so on. However, we will not conduct a post hoc test for this project because we are only interested in the general features that have most impact when predicting ckd, rather than the specific differences within a single feature.

We can conclude from this exploratory analysis that ckd can be predicted from low levels of sg, specifically, sg levels of 1.005, 1.01, 1.015, and 1.0174.

Machine Learning¶

Machine learning uses algorithms that become better at performing tasks by 'learning' through experience. We want to use machine learning to predict whether or not one may have CKD based on their genes and risk factors.

Gene Data Analysis with ML¶

We will create a model to understand what genes are presently upregulated or not within the CKD patients. The genes in patients with CKD can be compared to those without it, and that way we can see wht genes are more likely to be upregulated in the disease, thus playing a potnetial role in the disease. The machine learning model we will implement will try to decide which genes are upregulated in diseased patients, to be a target of further study of their role in CKD. We will use Logistic Regression, as the categorical data here(upregulated in disease or not) is dependent on the level of expression of genes in the diseased versus control patients. We will make the model based on the top upregulated genes and top down regulated genes we identified above as we must use one hot encoding to identify them, and we cannot do that for all 1500 genes since we have not statisitcally identified those as up/down regulated. Above, we used our statistcal tests to confirm that the genes are statistically signicantly classifiable as our most up or down regulated so we can identify them and use them as so in our ML model. Thus, we will use these 20 genes for the training model, and since there is so few, we will use cross validation to improve our results.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_predict
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

#one hot encoding, label the previously found top 10 most upregulated genes and downregulated genes and combine into a set to train
up["regulation"]= 1
down["regulation"]= 0
a= pd.concat([up, down], axis=0)
a=a.reset_index(drop=True)

#Train on sample gene expression
X = a[treatment+control]
#Target the regulation class
y =a[['regulation']]

#Train/Test
model = LogisticRegression()

# Perform stratified cross-validation
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=42, shuffle=True)


tlabels = []
plabels = []

# Iterate over folds
for train_index, test_index in skf.split(X, y):
    # Split the data into training and testing sets
    X_train, X_test = X.iloc[train_index].values, X.iloc[test_index].values
    y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index].values, y.iloc[test_index].values
    # Train model on the training data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # Predict on the testing data
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    # Store the true and predicted labels
    tlabels.extend(y_test)
    plabels.extend(y_pred)

#Evaluate Model
# Calculate Accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(tlabels, plabels)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)

# Generate and print the classification report
class_report = classification_report(tlabels, plabels)
print("Classification Report:")
print(class_report)

Risk Factor Data Analysis with ML¶

Based on the exploratory data analysis of the risk factor data, the variables that have the strongest correlation with the class variable are specific gravity, hemoglobin, packed cell volume, red blood cell count, albumin, hypertension, and diabetes, with specific gravity having the strongest correlation. We will use all seven predictor features to predict the classification of CKD cases.

Since there are many predictor features to account for, we need a ML model that can handle high dimensionality. Here, we will use a Support Vector Machine (SVM) model due to its ability to work well with high-dimensional data. A SVM is a supervised machine learning algorithm that finds the optimal hyperplane that separates different classes in the feature space. We will create a SVM model to predict whether or not one has ckd based on the 7 independent variables identified in our preliminary analysis (specific gravity, hemoglobin, packed cell volume, red blood cell count, albumin, hypertension, and diabetes).

Before we can use the SVM method, we need to normalize the data to deal with high variation and noise which could negatively effect the accuracy of the model. Here, we use z-score normalization due to the wide range of values that the numerical variables have.

In [26]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

X = rf_df[['spec_grav', 'hemoglobin', 'packed_cell_vol', 'red_b_cells', 'albumin', 'hypertension', 'diabetes']].values
Y = rf_df[['ckd_class']].values

# Split the data into training and testing sets.
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=20220621)

# Scale the input variable because SVM is dependent on differences in scale for distances
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Define and fit the risk factor SVM model
rfSVMlinear = svm.SVC(kernel='linear', C=0.01)
rfSVMlinear.fit(X_train_scaled, Y_train)

# Predict for the test set
Y_pred = rfSVMlinear.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Display the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False)
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.ylabel('True')
plt.show()

  y = column_or_1d(y, warn=True)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate decision function scores for the test set
decision_scores = rfSVMlinear.decision_function(X_test_scaled)

# Convert decision scores to probabilities using a sigmoid function
Y_pred_proba = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-decision_scores))

# Calculate and plot residuals
residuals = np.abs(Y_pred_proba - Y_test.flatten())

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(range(len(Y_test)), residuals, color='blue', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Residual-like Plot for Classification Model')
plt.xlabel('Data Index')
plt.ylabel('Residual')
plt.show()

In the above residual plot, the residuals are shown to be scattered and have no particular pattern. This demonstrates the fact that the SVM model's predictions are random, and therefore are not systematically biased toward overestimating or underestimating the true probabilities. This further suggests that this model is performing reasonably well.

Insights and Conclusions¶

Throughout this tutorial, we used data science to explore gene data and risk factor data to predict chronic kidney disease. Although our analysis is not completely comprehensive, it revealed some important insights about which genes and risk factors may lead to higher chances of developing chronic kidney disease. Overall, this can give insight to what people can look out for in CKD risk.

Gene Data¶

Regarding our analysis of gene data, our target was to identify which genes were playing a role in the presence of CKD, if any. Through our intial explorstory analysis, we learned which genes were the most upregulated and the most downregulated in diseased patients, as compared to our controls. We then were able to statisically confirm that the difference in the expression of these genes amaong CKD and control patients was significant, stiatiscally confirming the signifinace of labeling them as upregulated or downregulated. The changes in the expression of aa gene can affect the presnece of proteins relevant in a body and so it contributes to a disease. We next used logistic regression, after statistically cofirming the classification of our top genes as upregulated or not, to train our model to predict whether other genes in CKD may be classified as upregulated or not, based on how the expression is different in control and patient samples. We then applied this to the entire gene sequencing data, and predicted the regulation of the remainder of our genes based on this model. The model was able to accurately predict the regulation of the genes, and whether a gene is upregulated in a CKD patient. Overall, we found our top candidates for genes that may affect CKD, which need to be further studied to understand this and how they function. It would be great if you could apply the model to a single patient to assess the levels of their gene expression and know if any genes are upregulated at levels studed in other CKD samples, to predict their likelihood for CKD.

Risk Factor Data¶

Regarding our analysis of risk factors, our target feature was class, which indicated the classification of whether or not one has been diagnosed with chronic kidney disease. Through our initial exploratory analysis, we learned that the features that were most highly correlated with whether or not one had CKD were specific gravity, hemoglobin, packed cell volume, red blood cell count, albumin, hypertension, and diabetes. Furthermore, we discovered that specific gravity had the strongest correlation with the classification variable and that lower specific gravity levels typically indicate the presence of CKD. Then we used the support vector machines (SVM) machine learning method to use the values of the predictor features to predict the classification of whether or not CKD is present. The model was able to accurately predict above 90% of the instances. Our tutorial has shown that using the SVM model can be effective for classification tasks that have high dimensionality and that involve many variables.

By analyzing both gene and risk factor data, the chances of developing chronic kidney disease may be predicted and therefore allow those at higher risk to take proactive measures to avoid suffering from the disease and related conditions. Further studies can be done on the regaulated genes and understandnig how they specifically may affect CKD, to attempt to make therapies surrounding them.
